# Day 12 - Salesforce DX & Developer Workflow

## 1. What is Salesforce DX?

Salesforce DX (Developer Experience) is a modern development approach that helps teams build, test, and deploy Salesforce applications in a structured way.

It is source-driven, meaning code is stored and managed in tools like GitHub.

It helps developers:
- Work in teams
- Track changes
- Deploy safely
- Manage environments (sandbox, production)

---

## 2. Why CLI Matters

Salesforce CLI (Command Line Interface) helps developers interact with Salesforce using terminal commands instead of clicks.

### Benefits:
- Faster development
- Automation of tasks
- Easier deployment
- Better control over orgs and code

CLI improves developer productivity and reduces manual work.

---

## 3. Why GitHub Matters

GitHub is a version control system used to store and manage code.

### Benefits:
- Tracks code changes
- Allows collaboration
- Supports branching and merging
- Enables rollback to previous versions

It ensures safe and organized development in teams.

---

## 4. Team Collaboration Problems (Without Proper Tools)

If 10 developers work without version control:

- Code overwriting happens
- Conflicts in changes
- No history of updates
- Hard to debug issues
- No proper deployment tracking
- Risk of breaking production system

Without branches, everyone works on the same code → chaos.

---

## 5. Why Developers Use GitHub, CLI, and DX

Professional developers use these tools instead of browser clicks because:

- Browser clicks are slow and not scalable
- Large projects require automation
- Teams need collaboration
- Changes must be tracked
- Deployment must be controlled
- Errors must be reversible

These tools create a structured engineering workflow.

---

## 6. College Assignments vs Enterprise Development

| College Assignments | Enterprise Software |
|---------------------|---------------------|
| Single developer | Multiple teams |
| No version control | GitHub used |
| Manual submission | Automated deployment |
| No rollback needed | Rollback required |
| Simple logic | Complex business systems |
| No collaboration issues | Strict collaboration rules |

Enterprise systems require reliability, testing, and coordination across teams.

---

## 7. Real Engineering Thinking

Enterprise software development focuses on:

- Testing before deployment
- Collaboration between teams
- Controlled deployment process
- Rollback in case of failure
- High system reliability
- Handling large-scale users

Unlike simple assignments, enterprise systems must never break in production.

---

## 8. Reflection

After learning Salesforce workflow, I realized that professional software engineering is not just about writing code.

It is about:
- Working in teams
- Managing versions
- Deploying safely
- Maintaining system stability
- Ensuring scalability
- Handling real-world business requirements

Tools like DX, CLI, and GitHub are essential because they make enterprise development structured, safe, and reliable.

